The minister has declined to comment on the resignation of Eskom CEO Brian Molefe. JOHANNESBURG Cooperative Governance and Traditional Affairs Minister Des Van Rooyen has declined to comment on the resignation of Eskom CEO Brian Molefe, but has told Eyewitness News he will challenge the allegations made in the Public Protector's State of Capture report at the right time.Molefe resigned on Friday following the report's release, but he says his resignation is not an admission of guilt.Molefe features extensively in the report released last month and his close relationship with the Gupta family has been brought into question.Van Rooyen says he shares the sentiments of Public Protector Busisiwe Mkhwebane that people should not accuse those implicated in the State of Capture report of being guilty, until the matter goes through a judicial process. The court process is in the legislation. We will exercise our rights and wait for the opportune time to respond to the allegations leveled against some of us. However, he welcomed the release of the report, adding he will take action after the juridical inquiry.Read the Public Protector's full 'State of Capture' report below: State Capture Report 2016 by Primedia Broadcasting on Scribd(Edited by Shimoney Regter)